Key personnel are provided with personal laptop and emails/ Phoenix can be accessed from home. 7.12.2DOCUMENT AND SYSTEM BACKUPSThe Company maintains back-up of all office documents and systems in a computer server situated in a separate building. Similarly,hard copies of all documents are also archived in a separate premise.In the unfortunate event of any natural or man-made calamity, this arrangement allows the office to seamlessly continue its normalfunctions even after evacuating the normal office premises.7.13TRAINING AND DRILLSIn order to ensure that concerned staff are capable of dealing with emergencies, staff are to be adequately trained and drills areconducted in the office to cover the various possible emergencies that may be encountered.7.13.1PROCEDURES1) PlanningEmergency drills and exercises shall be carried out at intervals of not more than 6 months. The drill scenarios should be planned tocover as many contingencies from the list of possible contingencies (as per Section 7.5 ) in three years. Stake holders which mayinclude vessels, Charterers, third party contracting companies, field operators, class, local authorities and government agenciesshould be involved in planning and execution of the major exercises.The drills may be a ship/shore joint exercise in order to ensure overall emergency preparedness.Drills planned should be in compliance with the following:- A major exercise is to be carried out annually with each type of vessel.External parties and additional resources are to be used as appropriate to provide more realistic drills and exercises. These exercises should involvemobilization at least annually of external resources such as Class, MRCC, owners and other external parties/consultants.Incident scenarios should fully test the contingency plans. Table Top exercises are to be conducted with various vessels, should be realistic and should involvea number of contingencies to effectively train both ship and shore personnel.Alternative members are included in the planned exercises and drillsSome communication and mobilization exercises should be conducted outside the normal office hours.On-leave vessel staff is to be included at least once a year in the ship-shore drills to play various roles during the exercises.Media Consultant shall be included in company’s internal drill at an interval not exceeding one year.A matrix showing the annual exercise plan should be prepared by the Designated Person. This Matrix should cover at least oneexercise per type of ship per year. The exercise should be planned as per the type and trade of the vessel.2) InitiationThe Designated Person in consultation with the General Manager shall decide the nature of the emergency/emergencies to beexercised, the ship, media managers, owners, charterers, class, on-leave vessel staff etc to be involved and the date of the drill. Theship will be notified in advance accordingly. All messages related to the drill are to be marked “This is a drill”.3) ActionOn receipt of the notification message, staff will take the necessary action to deal with the situation until such time that the drill iscalled off.4) ReviewA review of the emergency preparedness and response shall be carried out in Company’s office.The review shall include a de-briefing to discuss effectiveness of the emergency procedures, the lessons learnt and agreeimprovements [if any] to be made to the company’s emergency procedures. Points arising from such debriefings meetings should besummarized, kept with individual drill’s record and shared with all the vessels in the fleet.The HSEQA Superintendent shall maintain records of these reviews. Actions requiring follow up shall be raised as ‘Observations’ and should include due date for completion. The Quality AssuranceManager is responsible to ensure that corrective action is taken in good time5) Record KeepingA record of drills carried out shall be maintained by the Designated Person, in the Ship / Shore drills file in form OQ10 (Casualty ERTRecord). The records shall include details of the entire proceedings in the chronological sequence of events since the first callreceived from the master and all documents and records related to the drill.The records of emergency exercises carried out with the vessels by the office and participants who have been involved in emergencydrills and exercises shall be maintained and filed in file EO 1.This file shall contain all the drill related correspondence suitably segregated.7.14POST INCIDENT REVIEW / REVIEW OF THE EMERGENCY PREPAREDNESSA detailed review to be carried out after each ship’s (own fleet vessel and/ or if information is available then other company vesselstoo) incident during the passage, to learn lessons and institute required corrective actions.a. By the MasterEffectiveness of any contingency plan can be best judged only in the event of an actual situation.
